AWS Session Manager Setup (Step by Step)

Step 1: Launch an EC2 Instance
Login to AWS Console.
Go to Amazon Web Services EC2.
Click Launch Instance.
Choose:
AMI: Amazon Linux 2023 or Ubuntu
Instance Type: t2.micro (Free Tier)
Create or select a key pair (not required for Session Manager, but okay to create one).
Launch the instance.

Step 2: Create an IAM Role
Go to IAM → Roles.
Click Create Role.
Select:
Trusted Entity Type: AWS Service
Use Case: EC2
Click Next.
Search and attach: AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore
Click Next.
Give Role Name:EC2-SSM-Role
Click Create Role.

Step 3: Attach IAM Role to EC2
Go to EC2 → Instances.
Select your instance.
Actions → Security → Modify IAM Role.
Select:
EC2-SSM-Role
Save.

Step 4: Verify SSM Agent

Amazon Linux 2/2023 usually has the SSM Agent pre-installed.

If connected through SSH, check:

sudo systemctl status amazon-ssm-agent

Start it if needed:

sudo systemctl start amazon-ssm-agent
sudo systemctl enable amazon-ssm-agent
Step 5: Ensure Internet Access

Your EC2 instance must be able to reach AWS Systems Manager.

For a public subnet:

Internet Gateway attached
Public IP assigned

Check:

ping amazon.com

If ping works, networking is generally okay.

Step 6: Wait for Managed Instance Registration

Go to:

Systems Manager → Managed Nodes

Your EC2 instance should appear after a few minutes.

Step 7: Connect Using Session Manager
Go to EC2 → Instances.
Select your instance.
Click Connect.
Select Session Manager tab.
Click Connect.

A terminal opens directly in your browser.
